Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Dalton G Rohde

records.addlTxt: 8:53 AM  Defendant Dalton G Rohde in court.  Attorney Joseph L Bauer in court for Dalton G Rohde.  Attorney Karl J. Kelz in court for State of Wisconsin Defendant enters a plea of NOT GUILTY to all counts and requests bond remain in place. So Ordered

8:32 AM DA calls case and states appearances. Defendant Dalton G Rohde in court.  Attorney Joseph L Bauer in court for Dalton G Rohde.  Attorney Karl J. Kelz in court for State of Wisconsin. DA Kelz states this matter is set for a preliminary Hearing. Court questions Attorney Bauer on proceeding. Attorney Bauer states they are ready to proceed. DA Kelz calls witness: Dylan Scheller a Deputy with the Price County Sheriff's  Office. Witness sworn. Direct questioning by DA Kelz. Witness identifies the defendant on record. Cross examination by Attorney Bauer. Attorney Bauer presents Officer Scheller with a Map of the town of Ogema which was pre marked as Exhibit #1. Witness identifies the exhibit. Continued cross examination by Attorney Bauer. Re-Direct by DA Kelz. Witness excused. Attorney Bauer moves to enter exhibit #1 into evidence. No objection by DA Kelz. Court receives Exhibit #1 into evidence. Court makes statements. Court finds probable cause exists that a crime was committed and binds DE over for trial. Information filed, acknowledged by parties and reading waived. proceed to arraignment
Preliminary hearing on October 4, 2022 at 08:30 am.
